sect1.para:
Although rates of bipolar I disorder are roughly equivalent between men and women, rates of bipolar II disorder may be higher for women than men (Diflorio & Jones,
         2010
      ). Similar rates of diagnosis of bipolar disorders are found around the world (American Psychiatric Association, 
         2013
      ; Mc Grath et al.,
         2023
      ). Age of onset is typically late adolescence to early adulthood although a smaller subset may develop bipolar disorders in midlife (American Psychiatric Association, 
         2013
      ). More than 70% of individuals with bipolar disorders
         bipolar disorders
       present with symptoms before the age of 25 (Jain & Mitra, 
         2024
      ; Moreno et al., 
         2007
      ) and the median age of onset of 20 years old worldwide (Mc Grath et al.,
         2023
      ). Due to the challenges of diagnosing bipolar disorder, it takes an average of 6–10 years after first contact with a provider for the diagnosis to be confirmed (Dagani et al., 
         2017
      ; Fritz et al., 
         2017
      ) with some research showing up to 14 years passing before proper diagnosis (Drancourt et al., 
         2013
      ).

Minority patients with bipolar disorder may have higher rates of comorbid substance abuse, homelessness, and involuntary hospitalizations when compared to White patients (Kilbourne et al.,
         2005
      ). It has also been posited that structural and cultural barriers experienced by minority patients, including poor access to healthcare and stigma, may lead them to present to care in more severe states of impairment as they may wait longer to seek help (Hwang et al., 
         2010
      ). Patients from differing cultures may tend to report distress in terms of somatic versus psychological symptoms, as has often been observed among Asian patients (Lin & Cheung, 
         1999
      ); this is important
         important
       for the assessor to keep in mind when evaluating whether a patient meets diagnostic criteria for bipolar disorder. Having said that, while it is important for clinicians to be aware of these types of cultural dynamics, it is equally important to not make assumptions about a patient’s clinical presentation based on their perceived race or ethnicity.
